Implementing a linked list in Rust for an embedded project with `no_std` and no heap allocation involves creating a custom linked list structure that uses fixed-size arrays instead of dynamically allocating memory. Here's a basic example to get you started:

```rust
#![no_std]

use core::mem;

struct Node {
    data: u32,
    next: Option<usize>,
}

struct LinkedList {
    data: [Node; 10], // Adjust size based on your project needs
    head: Option<usize>,
    available: usize,
}

impl LinkedList {
    fn new() -> Self {
        let mut data = [Node { data: 0, next: None }; 10]; // Initialize with default values
        for i in 0..9 {
            data[i].next = Some(i + 1);
        }
        LinkedList { data, head: Some(0), available: 0 }
    }

    fn add_node(&mut self, data: u32) {
        if self.available < self.data.len() {
            let index = self.available;
            self.available = self.data[index].next.unwrap_or(self.data.len()); // Update available index
            self.data[index] = Node { data, next: None };
            if let Some(head) = self.head {
                self.data[index].next = Some(head);
            }
            self.head = Some(index);
        }
    }

    fn print_list(&self) {
        let mut current = self.head;
        while let Some(index) = current {
            let node = &self.data[index];
            // Do something with the node data
            // For example, println!("{}", node.data);
            current = node.next;
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut list = LinkedList::new();
    list.add_node(42);
    list.add_node(57);
    list.print_list();
}
```

In this implementation, we use an array of `Node` structs to represent the linked list elements. The `next` field in each `Node` holds the index of the next node in the list. The `LinkedList` struct maintains the array of nodes, head pointer, and available index for new nodes.

Remember to adapt this implementation based on your specific requirements and constraints in the embedded project. Feel free to reach out if you need further assistance or optimizations.

