Certainly! Here is an example SQL code that calculates the distance between latitude and longitude coordinates using the Haversine formula:

```sql
DECLARE @lat1 FLOAT, @lon1 FLOAT, @lat2 FLOAT, @lon2 FLOAT; -- Coordinates for two points

SET @lat2 = 37.7749;
SET @lon2 = -122.4194;
SET @lat1 = 40.7128;
SET @lon1 = -74.0060;

DECLARE @R FLOAT;
SET @R = 6371; -- Earth's radius in kilometers

DECLARE @dLat FLOAT, @dLon FLOAT, @a FLOAT, @c FLOAT, @distance FLOAT;

SET @dLat = RADIANS(@lat2 - @lat1);
SET @dLon = RADIANS(@lon2 - @lon1);

SET @a = SIN(@dLat / 2) * SIN(@dLat / 2) + COS(RADIANS(@lat1)) * COS(RADIANS(@lat2)) * SIN(@dLon / 2) * SIN(@dLon / 2);
SET @c = 2 * ATN2(SQRT(@a), SQRT(1 - @a));

SET @distance = @R * @c;

SELECT @distance AS DistanceInKm;
```

You can plug in your own latitude and longitude coordinates for `@lat1`, `@lon1`, `@lat2`, and `@lon2` in the code above to calculate the distance.

