Sure! Here's an example of ASP.NET Core middleware that intercepts the action result object before serialization and hides specific fields:


```csharp
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http;
using Newtonsoft.Json;

public class FieldHidingMiddleware
{
    private readonly RequestDelegate _next;

    public FieldHidingMiddleware(RequestDelegate next)
    {
        _next = next;
    }

    public async Task Invoke(HttpContext context)
    {
        await _next(context);

        if (context.Response.StatusCode == 200)
        {
            string responseBody = await context.Response.BodyReader.ReadToEndAsync();

            // Hide specific fields before serialization
            // For example, hiding a field named "password"
            dynamic responseObject = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject(responseBody);
            responseObject.Password = null;

            string modifiedResponse = JsonConvert.SerializeObject(responseObject);

            context.Response.ContentLength = null;
            await context.Response.WriteAsync(modifiedResponse);
        }
    }
}
```

You can add this middleware to your ASP.NET Core pipeline to hide specific fields from the response before it gets serialized and sent to the client.

