Sure! Here's a simple implementation of an LRU (Least Recently Used) cache in Swift. This cache has a configurable capacity and follows the LRU eviction policy.

```swift
class LRUCache<Key: Hashable, Value> {
    private let capacity: Int
    private var cache: [Key: Value] = [:]
    private var keyOrder: [Key] = []

    init(capacity: Int) {
        self.capacity = capacity
    }

    func get(_ key: Key) -> Value? {
        if let value = cache[key] {
            // Move the key to the front of the keyOrder list
            if let index = keyOrder.firstIndex(of: key) {
                keyOrder.remove(at: index)
            }
            keyOrder.insert(key, at: 0)
            return value
        }
        return nil
    }

    func set(_ key: Key, _ value: Value) {
        if let _ = cache[key] {
            // Key already exists in the cache, move it to the front
            if let index = keyOrder.firstIndex(of: key) {
                keyOrder.remove(at: index)
            }
            keyOrder.insert(key, at: 0)
            cache[key] = value
        } else {
            if keyOrder.count == capacity {
                // Evict least recently used key
                let lruKey = keyOrder.removeLast()
                cache.removeValue(forKey: lruKey)
            }
            // Add the new key to the front
            keyOrder.insert(key, at: 0)
            cache[key] = value
        }
    }
}
```

This code defines a generic `LRUCache` class that can store key-value pairs with a maximum capacity. It uses a dictionary to store the key-value pairs and an array to keep track of the order in which the keys were accessed. The `get` method retrieves a value from the cache while updating the order of keys based on access time. The `set` method inserts a new key-value pair or updates an existing one while following the LRU eviction policy.

